              
[normal]              
[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Humanitarian Aid Relief Trust (HART)
[normal]Summary[bold]:[bold]Humanitarian Aid Relief Trust (HART) works with local partners, many of whom are trapped behind closed borders and “off  the radar screen” of the international community and major aid organisations.
[normal]Many of our colleagues in Burma are representative of ethnic national groups including the Shan, Karen, Karenni, Kachin, Chin and Rhohinga people.
[normal]The consistent reports we obtain during our visits highlight the increasing concern over recent developments in Burma.
[normal]While we welcome reforms and developments such as those relating to Aung San Suu Kyi and the release of a number of political prisoners, we are increasingly worried that the plight of ethnic national peoples is not improving and that representatives fear that they are being marginalised.  They are also worried that increase in international investment in Burma may lead to continuing exploitation of their resources and expropriation of their lands.
[normal]We therefore hope that DFID will make every effort to ensure that these peoples suffering from continuing conflict and massive displacement of civilians will receive the aid that they need.  Moreover, if the Burmese Government or State authorities do not facilitate access to these areas, we hope that DFID may increase its honourable and ethical policy of “indirect funding” through local reliable partners.
[normal]HART is privileged to work with some of these partners who take much-needed humanitarian aid to civilians trapped in these areas and, therefore, we know there is a proven track-record of reliability and accountability.
[normal]We would be very pleased to provide any additional information which might assist DFID to develop a policy to reach some of the civilians in Burma most in need of urgent aid.
[normal]Caroline Cox
[normal]              
